{{Infobox book | name = Listed: Dispatches from America's Endangered Species Act | title_orig = | translator = | image = Cover_of_Listed.jpg | caption = Hardcover, showing Florida panther. | author = [[Joe Roman]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = | series = | subject = [[Endangered Species]] | genre = | publisher = [[Harvard University Press]] | release_date = [[2011 in literature|2011]] | english_release_date = | media_type = Print ([[hardcover]]) | pages = | isbn = 9780674047518 | oclc= | followed_by = }} '''''Listed: Dispatches from America's Endangered Species Act''''' is a [[2011 in literature|2011]] book by [[Joe Roman]] that explores the history of the [[Endangered Species Act]] and the relationship between biodiversity and human well being. Healthy ecosystems, such as mangroves and dunes, for example, can act as barriers to natural catastrophes. The book received the 2012 Rachel Carson Environment Book Award from the [[Society of Environmental Journalists]].<ref name="arb1">{{cite web |title=Winners: SEJ 11th Annual Awards for Reporting on the Environment |work=[[Society of Environmental Journalists]] |url=http://www.sej.org/initiatives/winners-sej-11th-annual-awards-reporting-environment#RachelCarsonBook |date=October 17, 2012 |accessdate=July 15, 2017}} </ref>
