[[File:Operation Upshot test.ogv|thumb|320px|Video of Upshot–Knothole Grable test]] [[Image:uk-grable2.jpg|right|200px|thumb|A closeup of the [[mushroom cloud]] and fireball.]] '''Upshot–Knothole ''Grable''''' was a [[nuclear testing|nuclear weapons test]] conducted by the [[United States]] as part of [[Operation Upshot–Knothole]]. Detonation of the associated [[nuclear weapon]] occurred 19 seconds after its deployment at 8:30am [[Pacific Time zone|PDT]] (1530 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]) on May 25, 1953, in Area 5 of the [[Nevada Test Site]]. The codename ''Grable'' was chosen because the letter ''Grable'' is phonetic for G, as in "gun", since the warhead was a [[gun-type fission weapon]]. As a shell, or [[nuclear artillery|artillery-fired atomic projectile]] (AFAP), the device was the first of its kind. The test remains the only nuclear artillery shell ever actually fired in the [[Nuclear weapons testing|U.S. nuclear weapons test program]].
''Grable'' was the second of only four gun-type warheads ever detonated (the first was [[Little Boy]], the weapon used against [[Hiroshima]], the last two were test firings of the [[W33 (nuclear weapon)|W33]]; all other atomic weapons were [[Nuclear weapon design#Implosion type weapon|implosion-type]] weapons). The shell, designated a [[W9 (nuclear warhead)|Mark 9]] nuclear weapon, had a diameter of 280 mm (11.02 in), was 1380 mm (54.4 in) long and weighed 364 kg (803 lb). The [[M65 Atomic Cannon]] from which it was fired had a muzzle velocity of 625 m/s (2,060 ft/s), for a nominal range of {{convert|32|km|mi|abbr=on}}, and weighed 77 [[tonne|metric tons]] (85 [[short ton|t]]).
The detonation of ''Grable'' occurred 6 seconds after its firing.<ref name="Operation Upshot-Knothole DOE film">[http://www.nv.doe.gov/library/films/film.aspx?ID=1 "Operation Upshot–Knothole."] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080507020233/http://www.nv.doe.gov/library/films/film.aspx?ID=1 |date=2008-05-07 }} Department of Energy, 1953.</ref> It detonated over 11,000 yards (over 10 km, 6.25 mi) away from the gun it was fired from, over a part of the Nevada Test Site known as [[Frenchman Flat]]. The explosion was an [[air burst]] of 160 m (524 ft) above the ground (7 m (24 ft) above its designated burst altitude), 26 m (87 ft) west and 41 m (136 ft) south of its target (slightly uprange). Its yield was estimated at 15 [[TNT equivalent|kilotons]], around the same level as [[Little Boy]]. An anomalous feature of the blast was the formation of a [[Precursor (physics)|precursor]], a second shock front ahead of the incident wave. This precursor was formed when the [[shock wave]] reflected off the ground and surpassed the incident wave and Mach stem due to a heated ground air layer and the low burst height.<ref name="Operation Upshot-Knothole DOE film" /> It resulted in a lower overpressure, but higher overall dynamic pressure, which inflicted much more damage on [[Drag (physics)|drag]] sensitive targets such as jeeps and personnel carriers. This led strategists to rethink the importance of low air bursts in tactical [[nuclear warfare]].<ref>Kuran, Pete. [[Trinity and Beyond]]: The Atomic Bomb Movie. Visual Concept Entertainment, 1995.</ref>
Some images from Upshot–Knothole ''Grable'' were accidentally relabeled as belonging to the ''Priscilla'' shot from [[Operation Plumbbob]] in 1957. As a consequence many publications including official government documents have the photo mislabeled.<ref>Carey Sublette, "Operation Plumbbob," Nuclear Weapon Archive, [http://nuclearweaponarchive.org/Usa/Tests/Plumbob.html http://nuclearweaponarchive.org/Usa/Tests/Plumbob.html]. (accessed December 27, 2006).</ref>
Admiral [[Arthur W. Radford]], at the time the [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], and [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] [[Charles Erwin Wilson|Charles E. Wilson]] were present for the test.
